58→            StageId::DocsValidation,\n    59→            StageId::Review,\n    60→        ],\n    61→        flow_definition(FlowPreset::DocsChange).stages\n    62→    );\n    63→}\n    64→\n    65→#[test]\n    66→fn ci_improvement_flow_stage_order_matches_spec() {\n    67→    assert_eq!(\n    68→        &[\n    69→            StageId::CiPlan,\n    70→            StageId::CiUpdate,\n    71→            StageId::CiValidation,\n    72→            StageId::Review,\n    73→        ],\n    74→        flow_definition(FlowPreset::CiImprovement).stages\n    75→    );\n    76→}\n    77→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01HsEmyUbu9C7KXmVEUyYJ77","session_id":"3d9a0615-7442-4a66-ab27-f8160d110223","uuid":"e686edb4-e4be-4be5-9f6d-922fb7f5947b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013cmDyRfBzkmazdZ3zawjbz","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Product Requirements Document: csv2json\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→csv2json is a single-purpose, zero-configuration CLI tool written in Rust that converts CSV files to JSON with strict, predictable type inference. It ships as a single static binary under 5 MB with no runtime dependencies, no telemetry, and no network access.\n     6→\n     7→The core thesis is that **correctness is the killer feature**. Every existing tool in this space makes at least one critical mistake: silently converting zip codes (`07042`) to numbers, requiring a language runtime, bundling CSV-to-JSON as an afterthought inside a Swiss-army-knife tool, or offering only all-or-nothing type inference. csv2json occupies the gap — a focused tool that gets the defaults right so pipelines don't silently corrupt data.\n     8→\n     9→The market timing is favorable. xsv (10.8K GitHub stars), the most prominent Rust CSV tool, was archived in April 2025, leaving a visible gap. The data engineering market exceeds $120B with 87% of companies reporting skills gaps, meaning more generalist developers are building data pipelines and need tools that are safe by default. The Rust CLI renaissance (ripgrep, bat, fd, eza) has trained users to expect fast, correct, cross-platform binaries installable via `cargo install`.\n    10→\n    11→The MVP (v0.1) delivers file/stdin input, file/stdout output, per-cell type inference with leading-zero preservation, JSON Schema generation, BOM handling, configurable delimiters, and cross-platform binaries — estimated at ~660 lines of Rust with a ~700-line test suite.\n    12→\n    13→---\n    14→\n    15→## Goals & Non-Goals\n    16→\n    17→### Goals\n    18→\n    19→1. **Correct type inference by default.** Per-cell inference with strict, documented rules: `true`/`false` (case-sensitive) become booleans, empty strings and `null`/`NULL` become JSON null, numeric strings become numbers — but values with leading zeros are preserved as strings to prevent silent data corruption. Large integers (>2^53) are preserved as strings to avoid IEEE 754 precision loss.\n    20→\n    21→2. **Zero-configuration happy path.** `csv2json data.csv` produces correct output with no flags required. Sensible defaults (comma delimiter, compact output, fail-fast errors, type inference enabled) cover 90% of use cases.\n    22→\n    23→3. **Pipeline composability.** Behave as a well-mannered Unix citizen: data to stdout, diagnostics to stderr, meaningful exit codes, stdin support without special flags. Compose seamlessly with `cat`, `jq`, `grep`, and shell pipelines.\n    24→\n    25→4. **Cross-platform from day one.** Identical behavior on Linux (x86_64, aarch64), macOS (Intel + Apple Silicon), and Windows (x86_64). Pre-built binaries for all platforms on every release.\n    26→\n    27→5. **Schema discovery.** Standalone `--schema` mode emits a JSON Schema Draft 2020-12 document describing inferred column types, enabling validation pipeline setup and dataset exploration without writing transformation code.\n    28→\n    29→6. **Single static binary.** No runtime dependencies, no language interpreters, no shared libraries. Install via `cargo install`, download a binary from GitHub Releases, or install from a package manager.\n    30→\n    31→7. **Performance competitive with native tools.** Convert a 1 GB CSV file in under 20 seconds on commodity hardware. Row-by-row streaming keeps memory usage proportional to row size, not file size.\n    32→\n    33→### Non-Goals\n    34→\n    35→- **No Excel, Parquet, XML, or YAML input.** csv2json converts CSV. Other formats have dedicated tools.\n    36→- **No embedded scripting or plugin system.** Complex transformations belong downstream in `jq`, `mlr`, or application code.\n    37→- **No configuration files.** All behavior is controlled via CLI flags. No dotfiles, no environment variable magic, no hidden defaults.\n    38→- **No telemetry, update checks, or network access.** The binary is fully offline.\n    39→- **No date/time inference.** Dates remain strings. Date formats are ambiguous (`01/02/03`) and locale-dependent; inference would violate the correctness-first principle.\n    40→- **No multi-file batch processing in v0.1.** Single file per invocation. Batch mode is deferred to v0.3+.\n    41→- **No query language or row filtering in v0.1.** Filtering belongs in `jq` or `mlr` for the MVP; a minimal `--where` expression language is considered for v0.3+.\n    42→- **No non-UTF-8 encoding support in v0.1.** UTF-8 only. Encoding detection and `--encoding` flag are deferred to v0.2.\n    43→\n    44→---\n    45→\n    46→## User Stories\n    47→\n    48→### US-1: Data Pipeline Operator\n    49→> As a data engineer building ETL pipelines, I want to convert CSV exports from databases and vendor APIs into JSON so that downstream services can consume them without writing custom parsers. I need the tool to **preserve leading zeros** in fields like zip codes and part numbers, because silent numeric conversion has caused production incidents before. I need deterministic behavior so the same input always produces the same output, and I need nonzero exit codes on failure so my pipeline orchestrator (Airflow, Prefect, cron) can detect problems.\n    50→\n    51→**Acceptance criteria:**\n    52→- `csv2json vendors.csv -o vendors.json` produces a JSON array of objects with correct types\n    53→- A zip code column containing `07042` appears as `\"07042\"` (string), not `7042` (number)\n    54→- Exit code 0 on success, nonzero on any error\n    55→- Identical output for identical input across runs\n    56→\n    57→### US-2: Unix Pipeline Composer\n    58→> As a CLI power user, I want to pipe CSV data through csv2json and into jq for filtering: `cat users.csv | csv2json | jq '.[] | select(.active == true)'`. I need compact output by default (for piping) with a `--pretty` flag for human reading. I need stdin support without special flags — if no file argument is given, read from stdin.\n    59→\n    60→**Acceptance criteria:**\n    61→- `cat data.csv | csv2json` reads from stdin and writes JSON to stdout\n    62→- Output is compact (single line per default) for piping efficiency\n    63→- `csv2json data.csv --pretty` produces indented, human-readable JSON\n    64→- Boolean values inferred from `true`/`false` literals work with jq boolean filters\n    65→\n    66→### US-3: Schema-First API Developer\n    67→> As a backend developer receiving CSV files from external partners, I want to generate a JSON Schema from a sample CSV so I can set up validation in my API ingestion layer. I want `csv2json --schema partner_data.csv` to emit a Draft 2020-12 JSON Schema describing inferred column types.\n    68→\n    69→**Acceptance criteria:**\n    70→- `csv2json --schema data.csv` outputs a valid JSON Schema Draft 2020-12 document\n    71→- Schema includes `$schema`, `type: \"array\"`, `items.properties` with per-column types\n    72→- Mixed-type columns produce union type arrays (e.g., `{\"type\": [\"number\", \"string\"]}`)\n    73→- All columns appear in the `required` array\n    74→- Schema-only CSV (headers, no data rows) produces properties typed as `{\"type\": \"null\"}`\n    75→\n    76→### US-4: DevOps Engineer\n    77→> As a DevOps engineer, I maintain inventory data in CSV spreadsheets that need to be converted to JSON for Terraform and Ansible. I need the tool to handle CSVs with duplicate column headers (common after spreadsheet merges) without crashing — warn me, but don't block the pipeline. I need the tool to work identically on my macOS laptop, the Linux CI runners, and the Windows jump box.\n    78→\n    79→**Acceptance criteria:**\n    80→- Duplicate column headers produce a warning on stderr but do not cause an error\n    81→- Last-value-wins semantics for duplicate headers\n    82→- Output is byte-identical across Linux, macOS, and Windows for the same input\n    83→\n    84→### US-5: Cautious Data Analyst\n    85→> As a data analyst exploring an unfamiliar CSV dataset, I want to convert it to JSON to load into a notebook. I want booleans to only be `true`/`false` (not `yes`/`1`/`TRUE`), nulls to be explicit, and numbers to not lose precision. If the CSV has no headers, I want `--no-header` to auto-generate sensible keys.\n    86→\n    87→**Acceptance criteria:**\n    88→- Only literal `true` and `false` (case-sensitive) become JSON booleans\n    89→- `True`, `TRUE`, `yes`, `1` remain strings\n    90→- `--no-header` generates keys `field_0`, `field_1`, `field_2`, etc.\n    91→- Large integers (>2^53) are preserved as strings, not truncated by floating-point representation\n    92→\n    93→### US-6: CI/CD Integration Engineer\n    94→> As a developer integrating csv2json into CI pipelines, I want shell completions for bash, zsh, fish, and PowerShell so my team can discover flags without reading docs. I want distinct exit codes per error category so I can write conditional logic in shell scripts.\n    95→\n    96→**Acceptance criteria:**\n    97→- `csv2json --completions bash` outputs a valid bash completion script\n    98→- Exit codes: `0` success, `1` I/O error, `2` CSV parse error, `3` invalid arguments, `4` schema error\n    99→- `csv2json --version` outputs `csv2json 0.1.0`\n   100→\n   101→---\n   102→\n   103→## Functional Requirements\n   104→\n   105→### FR-1: Input Handling\n   106→\n   107→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   108→|---|---|---|\n   109→| FR-1.1 | Accept a single file path as a positional argument: `csv2json data.csv` | Must |\n   110→| FR-1.2 | Read from stdin when no file argument is provided: `cat data.csv \\| csv2json` | Must |\n   111→| FR-1.3 | When stdin is a TTY (interactive terminal) and no file argument is given, print a help hint to stderr and wait for input | Must |\n   112→| FR-1.4 | Detect and strip UTF-8 BOM (`0xEF 0xBB 0xBF`) from the beginning of input | Must |\n   113→| FR-1.5 | Reject non-UTF-8 input with exit code 2 and a clear error message identifying the byte offset of the invalid sequence | Must |\n   114→| FR-1.6 | Accept only a single file per invocation; multiple file arguments produce exit code 3 | Must |\n   115→\n   116→### FR-2: Output Handling\n   117→\n   118→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   119→|---|---|---|\n   120→| FR-2.1 | Write JSON output to stdout by default | Must |\n   121→| FR-2.2 | Support `-o` / `--output <PATH>` to write to a file; overwrite if the file exists | Must |\n   122→| FR-2.3 | Compact JSON output by default (no unnecessary whitespace) | Must |\n   123→| FR-2.4 | `--pretty` flag produces indented JSON (2-space indent) | Must |\n   124→| FR-2.5 | Output is a JSON array of objects in data mode, where each CSV row becomes one object | Must |\n   125→| FR-2.6 | Object keys appear in CSV column order (insertion-order preservation) | Must |\n   126→| FR-2.7 | Empty CSV (headers only, no data rows) produces `[]` | Must |\n   127→| FR-2.8 | Ensure binary-mode stdout on Windows (no `\\n` → `\\r\\n` translation) | Must |\n   128→\n   129→### FR-3: CSV Parsing\n   130→\n   131→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   132→|---|---|---|\n   133→| FR-3.1 | Parse CSV per RFC 4180 baseline via the `csv` crate | Must |\n   134→| FR-3.2 | Default delimiter is comma; configurable via `--delimiter <CHAR>` | Must |\n   135→| FR-3.3 | `--delimiter` accepts literal characters and the `\\t` escape sequence for tab | Must |\n   136→| FR-3.4 | First row is treated as the header row by default | Must |\n   137→| FR-3.5 | `--no-header` flag: treat all rows as data, auto-generate keys `field_0`, `field_1`, ... | Must |\n   138→| FR-3.6 | Trim leading and trailing whitespace from all cell values before inference | Must |\n   139→| FR-3.7 | Trim leading and trailing whitespace from header values | Must |\n   140→\n   141→### FR-4: Duplicate Header Handling\n   142→\n   143→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   144→|---|---|---|\n   145→| FR-4.1 | When duplicate column headers are detected, emit a warning to stderr identifying the duplicated header name(s) | Must |\n   146→| FR-4.2 | For duplicate headers, last-value-wins: the rightmost column with a given name determines the value in the output object | Must |\n   147→\n   148→### FR-5: Ragged Row Handling\n   149→\n   150→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   151→|---|---|---|\n   152→| FR-5.1 | By default, rows with fewer fields than headers are null-padded (missing fields become `null`) | Must |\n   153→| FR-5.2 | `--strict` flag: rows with fewer or more fields than the header row cause an error (exit code 2) | Must |\n   154→| FR-5.3 | Without `--strict`, rows with more fields than headers silently drop extra fields | Should |\n   155→\n   156→### FR-6: Type Inference Engine\n   157→\n   158→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   159→|---|---|---|\n   160→| FR-6.1 | Type inference is per-cell: each value is independently inferred regardless of other values in the same column | Must |\n   161→| FR-6.2 | Inference is enabled by default; `--no-inference` emits all values as JSON strings (except empty cells, which are still `null`) | Must |\n   162→| FR-6.3 | **Null inference:** empty string `\"\"` → `null`; literal `null`/`NULL`/`Null` (case-insensitive) → `null` | Must |\n   163→| FR-6.4 | **Null inference for whitespace-only cells:** trim first, then if empty → `null` | Must |\n   164→| FR-6.5 | **Boolean inference:** only case-sensitive `true` → `true`, `false` → `false`; all other variants (`True`, `TRUE`, `yes`, `1`, `on`) remain strings | Must |\n   165→| FR-6.6 | **Numeric inference:** valid numeric strings become JSON numbers; integers, decimals, negative numbers, and numbers with a leading `+` sign are accepted | Must |\n   166→| FR-6.7 | **Leading-zero preservation:** any numeric string with a leading zero (except plain `0`) is preserved as a string (`007` → `\"007\"`, `0.5` → `0.5`, `0` → `0`) | Must |\n   167→| FR-6.8 | **Scientific notation:** strings matching `[+-]?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?[eE][+-]?\\d+` are parsed as JSON numbers | Must |\n   168→| FR-6.9 | **Large number precision:** integers with absolute value > 2^53 are preserved as strings to avoid IEEE 754 precision loss | Must |\n   169→| FR-6.10 | **NaN/Infinity:** `NaN`, `Infinity`, `-Infinity`, `+Infinity` (any casing) remain strings (not valid JSON numbers) | Must |\n   170→| FR-6.11 | **Negative zero:** `-0` is treated as numeric `0` (JSON number `0`) | Must |\n   171→| FR-6.12 | **Quoted field inference:** CSV quoting is structural, not semantic; quoted values are inferred the same as unquoted values | Must |\n   172→| FR-6.13 | **Embedded JSON:** cell values that look like JSON objects or arrays are kept as strings (not parsed) | Must |\n   173→| FR-6.14 | **Empty cells with `--no-inference`:** empty cells produce `null` regardless of the `--no-inference` flag | Must |\n   174→\n   175→### FR-7: Schema Mode\n   176→\n   177→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   178→|---|---|---|\n   179→| FR-7.1 | `--schema` flag: output a JSON Schema Draft 2020-12 document instead of data | Must |\n   180→| FR-7.2 | Schema includes `\"$schema\": \"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema\"` | Must |\n   181→| FR-7.3 | Root schema type is `\"array\"` with `items` describing the row object structure | Must |\n   182→| FR-7.4 | Each CSV column becomes a property in `items.properties` with inferred type(s) | Must |\n   183→| FR-7.5 | Mixed-type columns use union type arrays: `{\"type\": [\"number\", \"string\"]}` | Must |\n   184→| FR-7.6 | All columns appear in the `required` array | Must |\n   185→| FR-7.7 | Headers-only CSV (no data rows) emits schema with all properties typed as `{\"type\": \"null\"}` | Must |\n   186→| FR-7.8 | Schema mode respects `--pretty` for indented output | Must |\n   187→| FR-7.9 | Schema mode exit code for schema generation errors is `4` | Must |\n   188→\n   189→### FR-8: Error Handling\n   190→\n   191→| ID | Requirement | Priority |\n   192→|---|---|---|\n   193→| FR-8.1 | Default error mode is fail-fast: exit on the first error encountered | Must |\n   194→| FR-8.2 | Error messages are human-readable and written to stderr | Must |\n   195→| FR-8.3 | Error messages include context where applicable: line number, column index, problematic value | Must |\n   196→| FR-8.4 | Exit code `0`: success | Must |\n   197→| FR-8.5 | Exit code `1`: I/O error (file not found, permission denied, write failure) | Must |\n   198→| FR-8.6 | Exit code `2`: CSV parse error (malformed row, encoding error, ragged row in strict mode) | Must |\n   199→| FR-8.7 | Exit code `3`: invalid arguments (unknown flag, bad delimiter value, conflicting flags) | Must |\n   200→| FR-8.8 | Exit code `4`: schema generation error | Must |"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01D1YGYYF5pXopdBJ1HtvaN6","session_id":"3d9a0615-7442-4a66-ab27-f8160d110223","uuid":"e18f7849-7519-4108-aabb-3b2db71193af"}
